column1: Inquiry into admission requirements^Hello
column2: \r\n\r\nI'm writing to request more information on the admissions requirements for your Analytics Program. I have a BA from New York University
column3: and I see that your preferred undergraduate degrees are in quantitative fields
column4: as most programs are. \r\n\r\nSince entering the working world I've gained on-the-job experience in statistical analysis and data management. I'm proficient in MySQL and familiar with Oracle-based SQL. I realized that the data projects I did in my job were by far the most fun projects I had
column5: and that I should turn that passion into a full-time career. \r\n\r\nI'm currently taking courses online in Statistics
column6: R and Python for fun and to prep for a Data Science program. The MSc at Northwestern looks like a great fit for me
column7:

column1: query : TOEFL expectations^Dear Madam / Sir
column2:
Thank you very much for your quick reply. 


I am quoting point 7 from the section "Application Materials" on the webpage of Master of Science in Analytics program at Northwestern University. (http://www.analytics.northwestern.edu/admission/Application%20Materials.html). This says I should have taken the TOEFL test later than September 24
column3: 2012. I have taken the test on February 11
column4: 2012 and scored 102 on 120. I intend to apply by November 2013 for the course starting fall 2014. Will I still be eligible to apply for this course with the score of the test taken on February 11
column5:
2012? Kindly confirm.


" 7) English Proficiency - TOEFL/IELTS (submission details below)
If you do not possess a degree from an institution where English is the primary language of instruction
column6: then you must demonstrate your English proficiency by sitting for either the TOEFL or the IELTS.\r\nTest scores must be less than two years old at the date of matriculation (for the 2014-15 cohort

column8:
I am concerned that the employment gap will impact my admissions.

column1: application^Dear Officer
column2: I just got rejected from MS in Analytics in Northwestern University. Although I know the application size must be large and there must be a lot of excellent applicants
column3:
I was really disappointed. 


This program has been my dream program since last year when Northwestern University came to UW Madison for graduate school fair. I have been striving for getting into this program ever since. I joined the honors program in statistics and 
looked for research opportunities. It is true that the application process did help me know who I was
column4:
who I am and who I should be. I have spent a lot of time only to find out that I am not much into academic research compared to put my ability and passion into workplace. I really hope to start a career-oriented master program to better equip myself. MS in analytics is no doubt the perfect one.


I really want to know why I got rejected and I do really hope that the committee can reconsider my application.


Best

column1: Application^Dear Victoria:\r\nHow are you doing?\r\nGreetings from Lan Ma
column2: Beijing China.\r\nToday is your application deadline. Could you please receive my application files through your application system and also through your email. I have a strong wish to enter Northwestern University. I have good courses preparation and some working experience as an assistant business analyst
column3: which I think will lead me well to my career in analytics.  My weak point is that I did not perform well in my TOEFL test.  I really hope that you could accept me.  On the one hand
column4: I can perform enough TOEFL score in my next test
column5: and on the other hand
column6: I can take some English courses if necessary after I enter the program.  Please believe my ability to accomplish my study goal. As far as I know that quite a few US universities give potential good students conditional admission.  I hope you can do me this favor
column7: too. I would be moved to tears.\r\nLast night
column8: I myself made a short video clip about my personal introduction
column9: and wish you could know more about me.  It is just for your reference.\r\nI lay all my hope on Northwestern University
column10: which is the only school I will go to without any hesitation as long as you could accept me.\r\nI have a crush on the Great Lakes.  When I was in my primary school
column11: I stayed in Toronto for some time
column12: and saw the Great Lakes which left me a deep memory.  Even now I could still see the beautiful lakes
column13: the Niagara Fall
column14: etc. Therefore
column15: I would like to return to the Great Lakes.\r\nI will dream Evanston
column18: the old Sears Tower
column20: Chicago Bulls
column21: Navy Pier
column24:
when you will release the admission result.
I am looking forward to hearing from you and seeing you at Evanston.
May God bless me.

column1: Regarding SOP for MSiA program^Hi
column2:
I have a query regarding the SOP for MSiA program.

The SOP question has three parts:

*	Why are you applying to the Master of Science in Analytics at Northwestern University? Please include in your answer why you are interested in analytics as well as your career goals.
*	What skills or abilities do you hope to strengthen in the program? (one paragraph)
*	Describe a trend that will influence analytics over the next 5 years? (one paragraph) 

It states that the statement should be 500 word or less
column3:
and individual elements meet the criteria.

My query is whether each of the three question can individually be 500 words each or all 3 combined have to be 500 words or less.

I have written on the SOP with 500 words for each question (totally ~1500 words). Please confirm my understanding.

Thanks
column4:
Sachin

column1: Campus Visit Resources^To Northwestern Analytics' Admissions Office
column2: I hope this email finds you well. I am writing because I'm an applicant to the MSA program
column3: and I'm looking for any resources or advice you might be able to give me in advance of a visit to Northwestern's campus next week. I will be in Chicago this upcoming Friday-Sunday for a Loyola University debate tournament
column4: and as I'm in the final stages of submitting an application
column5: I thought this would be an ideal chance to capitalize on a trip I'll already be making in order to visit Northwestern's campus during the day on Thursday
column6: February 13. \r\n\r\nMost of the resources I found were focused on undergraduate campus visits
column7:
and the sample classes in the undergraduate Industrial Engineering/Management Science section all seem to occur on M/W/F only.

That being said - and recognizing that not all of these will be feasible - information or advice on any of the following fronts would be greatly appreciated: 
--Where on campus is the MSA program and the bulk of its classes situated? 
--Would it be possible to sit in on one of the 2014 cohort classes
column8:
to get a sense of how classes are conducted? 
--Would it be possible to pass my contact information onto a current student? I'd love to talk to buy coffee/lunch for a someone currently enrolled and get their perspective on the program. 


Thank you for your time
column9: and best wishes

column1: Data Analytics and Natural Sciences^Dear Lindsay Montanari
column2:
This afternoon I attended the information session for the Master of Science in Analytics program.  I currently work at the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources as a Management and Data Analyst.  Recently our agency has gotten more and more involved in the "Big Data" movement and I'm seeing a big need for good data analysis skills in the natural sciences.

I was wondering if Northwestern ever partnered with public agencies that work in this area such as NOAA
column3: EPA
column4: or state climate and natural resource agencies. I'm very interested in data science and data analytics
column5: but specifically in their application in the natural sciences.\r\n\r\nMy background is actually in both IT and the Natural Sciences.  My undergraduate degree is in Biology and Environmental Science
column6:
however I also took several computer science courses and I'm currently working on a Java Development and SQL Certificate at a local college. In my current job I manage the development of a web application and database system to track the outcomes of conservation projects across the state. I lead a team of programmers and conservation scientists to develop this system.

I'm very interested in this program as I feel it will really help me develop and expand the analytical skills I need.  I'm just wondering if it would be possible to connect some of the work I'd do in the program to natural resource data problems.

Thanks

column1: from an interested applicant^My name is Jeffrey Wan and I'm a prospective student who's interested in Northwestern's Masters in Data Sciences program. I'm have some questions regarding the program and I was hoping you could help make a decision as to which program to apply to.\r\n\r\nAllow me to give you some background information about my career: I currently work at an options market-making and high-frequency firm
column2: I also work part-time at a policy advocacy organization for Asian American families and children
column3: I previously have worked as a senior trader at an equity trading firm
column4: professional poker player
column5: and tennis coach
column6: and I graduated from Amherst College in 2008. Throughout my career in trading and poker
column7: I have seen just how powerful analyzing data can be: it can save people time
column8: resources
column9:
and eliminate theories that are widely at variance with data. I would like the opportunity to invest in myself by going back to school. 

Here are some facts about myself and some questions I had about the requirements:
1) I took a college-level calculus course in high school and did well on the AP. Does this count still? I also recently relearned calculus at my last job as a derivatives trader. I also relearned some calculus on Khan Academy and Coursera.
2) I took a Coursera course in comp sci and I have programmed some applications in c#. Do I still need to take a college-level comp sci course? Is this a prereq?
3) I haven't taken linear algebra. Does this course typically have prerequisites? I don't have any coursework in matricies or vectors or spaces. Is this a problem? If so
column10:
is this something that I can take after being admitted to the program? Are there typically prereqs for linear algebra?

column2:

column3: and also Queen Mary

column5: CAN I HAVE A WAIVER ON TOEFL?\r\n\r\n\tI am studing in beijing university of posts and telecommunications?and Queen Mary at the same time?during the four years study?I was teached by professor in QM?and will gain the degree in Engineering of BUPT and degree in management of QM.Our school and QM is the cooperation in running joint program
column6: means I am also two school students
column7: studing in Beijing but teached by the QM. The teacher will teach us almost all of the courses.Our exams is also tested in English
column8:

How are you doing?

I am an international applicant interested in the MS Analytics program from your esteemed university.

Could you please answer to my following queries?

2) Do I need to send the official score of TOEFL through ETS or uploading a scanned copy of the official score report is sufficient?

3) The website says that during application phase uploading scanned copies of the transcript will suffice the purpose, however prior to admission the transcripts need to be sent over mail to your admission department. Please confirm. If uploading scanned copy is fine during application, could you please look into the attached file and confirm if this will suffice?

4) I have a 6+ years experience in Analytics field in India after I completed my post graduation in 2007. In such a case, your website says to get all the 3 recommendations from professional field. Is it an absolute must because getting 3 recommendations while you are at work may be challenging at times?

5) What % of the tuition fees can be obtained by fellowship/ scholarship/ assistantships ?


Looking forward to your reply.


Thanks,

Arnab Chatterjee

column1: Cancelling Enrollment in the Analytics Program^Dear Northwestern Analytics
column2: I am sincerely grateful for the offer of enrollment in the Northwestern Analytics program and the additional scholarship offer.  I wanted enter the program so that I could get a position applying analytics for social good.  I have been offered the opportunity to work in analytics for TMC
column3:
a division of C.H. Robinson.  The role is directly in line with my goals because I would be using analytics to improve the efficiency of transportation networks which will reduce the cost of goods to the end user and greenhouse gas emissions by reducing fuel usage.  After agonizing over the decision for over a month I have decided to accept the job offer and not pursue an in class masters degree at this time.  

 

I have a great deal of respect for Northwestern University and I hope to enroll in the online predictive analytics program in the near future.  I recognize that this must be a substantial inconvenience and I humbly apologize
column4:
but I will not be attending this September.

 

Warmest regards
column5:
Erik Osland
